module.exports = {"title":"Debian and NoSQL Storage Systems","date":"2010-03-01T00:00:00.000Z","tags":"debian,mongodb,nosql,redis","__content":"<p>After reviewing a bunch of &quot;NoSQL&quot; style <a href=\"http://www.docunext.com/blog/2010/02/redis-memcachedb-or-couchdb.html\">document-based</a> / <a href=\"http://www.docunext.com/blog/2010/02/redis-and-tokyo-tyrant.html\">key-value</a> storage systems, I decided to move forward with four of them and install them on production and demonstration machines.</p>\n<p>On the production machines, I stuck with Debian&#39;s &quot;testing&quot; repository, currently dubbed &quot;Squeeze&quot;. As such, I installed MemcacheDB and Redis.</p>\n<p>On a demonstration machine, I temporarily added the unstable repository, &quot;Sid&quot;, as well as the MongoDB repository for the stable Debian distribution, &quot;Lenny&quot; (which required I add the official Lenny repository as well). With these extra repositories, I was able to install tokyotyrant and mongodb. :-)</p>\n"}

