module.exports = {"title":"Rudy Tidy Gem","date":"2010-03-21T00:00:00.000Z","tags":"gems,ruby","__content":"<p>I just tried using the Ruby Tidy gem, the one hosted at Ruby Forge. Alas, its not compatible with Ruby 1.9.1:</p>\n<pre class=\"sh_log\">\n/var/lib/gems/1.9.1/gems/tidy-1.1.2/lib/tidy/tidybuf.rb:5:in `<class:Tidybuf>': uninitialized constant DL::Importable (NameError)\n    from /var/lib/gems/1.9.1/gems/tidy-1.1.2/lib/tidy/tidybuf.rb:3:in `<top (required)>'\n    from /var/lib/gems/1.9.1/gems/tidy-1.1.2/lib/tidy.rb:25:in `require'\n    from /var/lib/gems/1.9.1/gems/tidy-1.1.2/lib/tidy.rb:25:in `<module:Tidy>'\n    from /var/lib/gems/1.9.1/gems/tidy-1.1.2/lib/tidy.rb:21:in `<top (required)>'\n</pre>\n\n<p>Thankfully, there is another Tidy Gem which is! As an added bonus, it uses the ffi gem. As a side note, the <a href=\"http://blog.headius.com/2008/10/ffi-for-ruby-now-available.html\">ffi</a> gem is awesome!</p>\n<p>It actually took some digging to find it, so here&#39;s a link to the github project:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://github.com/libc/tidy_ffi\">http://github.com/libc/tidy_ffi</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>And the author&#39;s website:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://libc.st/\">http://libc.st/</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The docs are a bit sparse, so here&#39;s an example of how I&#39;m using it:</p>\n<pre class=\"sh_ruby\">\nTidyFFI::Tidy.new(output, :show_body_only => 1, :output_xml => 1, :numeric_entities => 1).clean\n</pre>\n\n<p>Basically, <a href=\"http://www.labs.docunext.com/demo/dlabzapp2/debdocs/view/tidy-doc/index.html\">tidy options</a> can be used when their hyphens (-) are switched with underscores (_).</p>\n"}

