module.exports = {"title":"No lines in buffer","date":"2010-10-10T00:00:00.000Z","__content":"<p>This is an annoying little bug in Vim when using the remote browsing capabilities of netrw.</p>\n<p>Its annoying because I have to press enter to continue! Thankfully there is a quick workaround that <em>sort of</em> works:</p>\n<pre class=\"sh_sh\">\n:set ch=2\n</pre>\n\n<p>That gives the vim console enough room to display two  &quot;--No lines in buffer--&quot; errors without asking the user to continue.</p>\n<p>There has got to be a way to silence this! I tried:</p>\n<pre class=\"sh_sh\">\nsilent! g:netrw_scp_cmd\n</pre>\n\n<p>and:</p>\n<pre class=\"sh_sh\">\nlet g:netrw_silent = 1\nlet g:netrw_use_noswf= 0\n</pre>\n\n<p>with no luck. I also tried disabling all my other plugins, but that didn&#39;t work either.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://groups.google.com/group/vim_use/browse_thread/thread/57c20cae297736ac\">http://groups.google.com/group/vim_use/browse_thread/thread/57c20cae297736ac</a></li>\n</ul>\n"}

