module.exports = {"title":"An HTTP Proxy Written in PHP Using LibCurl","date":"2010-12-29T00:00:00.000Z","tags":"php","__content":"<p>Thanks to PHP, I found it actually quite easy to write a quick and dirty HTTP proxy.</p>\n<p>The one I came up with is definitely not a standards compliant proxy that supports all of the HTTP protocol (it might be possible, but I didn&#39;t try).</p>\n<p>Why would I do such a thing? I had to do so in order to access a remote site that had network based security setup to provide access to content from a specific IP. That&#39;s the catch, though. Since the server that is running PHP has tons of IP addresses routed to it, it wasn&#39;t a total cakewalk to get PHP to use a specific one of them. How did I manage that? Only thanks to PHP&#39;s binding to libCurl.</p>\n"}

