module.exports = {"title":"Travis CI is Awesome","comments":[{"author":"gretch","email":"gapolgretchen@gmail.com","ip":"112.202.98.116","url":null,"date":"09/30/2011 06:33:10 PM","text":"Hi,<br/><br/>I would like to setup Travis CI for my private repos as well. Was it a success?<br/><br/>Thanks\n"},{"author":"Albert","email":"albert.lash@savonix.com","ip":"71.178.29.218","url":null,"date":"10/03/2011 08:44:44 PM","text":"Hi gretch, I haven't set it up locally yet...\n"}],"date":"2011-08-13T00:00:00.000Z","tags":"ruby","__content":"<p>I&#39;m trying out Travis CI for <a href=\"http://www.regdel.com/\">Regdel</a> and it is awesome! I&#39;m also using it for rack-xsl, and I finally got that to pass.</p>\n<p>It took me thirteen tries to get rack-xsl to pass, but that&#39;s because my current workstation isn&#39;t setup to test it.</p>\n<p>What does the CI stand for? Its means continuous integration, and it is a big help when rapidly developing software.</p>\n<p>I have hit some stumbling blocks:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Gems that are from git repositories, like rails-3.1. I had to create local copies of them and then add all my vendor/cache gems to the git repository. Yuck.</li>\n<li>Travis-ci doesn&#39;t seem to like bcrypt_ext.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>My next step will be to try and setup a Travis CI server for private projects.</p>\n<p></p>\n"}

