module.exports = {"title":"AuthLogic Configuration Options and Examples","date":"2011-09-22T00:00:00.000Z","tags":"authentication,authlogic,devise,rack,ruby","__content":"<p>AuthLogic was the first authentication gem I chose for Rails 3.1. It works, but I have issues with the documentation - its not clear, and there just aren&#39;t enough configuration examples to figure out how to set it up.</p>\n<p>Its ironic, because the documentation says...</p>\n<blockquote><pre>\nA code example can replace a thousand words...\n</pre></blockquote>\n\n<p>But one of the examples they provide is:</p>\n<pre class=\"sh_ruby\">\nclass User < ActiveRecord::Base\n  acts_as_authentic do |c|\n    c.my_config_option = my_value\n  end # the configuration block is optional\nend\n</pre>\n\n<p>Ugh! Seriously. Why not use a <em>real</em> configuration option??</p>\n<p>From what I&#39;ve gathered, there are two places that options are set:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>User</li>\n<li>UserSession</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For User, configuration options are set in a block, like so:</p>\n<pre class=\"sh_ruby\">\n 1 class User < ActiveRecord::Base\n 2   acts_as_authentic do |c|\n 3     c.logged_in_timeout = 1.day\n 4   end\n</pre>\n\n<p>and for UserSession, they are set with class methods, like so:</p>\n<pre class=\"sh_ruby\">\n  1 class UserSession < Authlogic::Session::Base\n  2   self.logout_on_timeout = true\n  3   self.last_request_at_threshold = 10.minutes\n  4 end\n</pre>\n\n<p>I hope you find this useful, I sure could have used a page like this tonight!</p>\n<p>NOTE: I&#39;ve since switched to Devise, but not for my complaints mentioned above. I really like the fact that Devise can hook right into Rack.</p>\n"}

